Dear DELTA MEDICAL EQUIPMENT,
We are requesting medical records for each claim submitted on the enclosed spreadsheet. UnitedHealthcare has
authorized Optum to conduct a pre-payment review of services provided to the patient listed. More information
about the relationship between Optum and UnitedHealthcare is at the end of this letter.
We will use the medical records to help determine eligible expenses under the patient's health plan. The
information will help ensure that any claim payment made to you is accurate and, in turn, help reduce
overpayment recovery requests. Please note that the review will not examine claims for medical necessity or
utilization.

hold. When you send us the information we need, we will process the claim and notify you of our decision. If the
information is not received by the deadline, the claim may be denied.

Equipment/Homecare Needs and Medical Justification:
Incontinence supplies are needed due to patient's inability to control bowel and bladder functions. in order to
maintain personal hygiene and skin integrity it is important to keep diapered area clean and dry. Prolonged
exposure to urine and stool increases risk of skin irritation and breakdown. Patient would benefit from non-
acholic cleansing wipes to maintain clean skin, reduce risk of breakdown and maintain skin integrity.
Speech generating device is medically necessary for this patient. The patient's diagnosis of Noonan syndrome
and global developmental delays creates the need for this speech generating device. Patient has intellectual
disability and mixed receptive and expressive language disorder diagnoses and requires a speech generating
device. Patient cannot use speech functionally to communicate medically essential needs and should be
evaluated for a speech generating device.
Home Care Services
Due to their diagnosis of Noonan syndrome and developmental delay, this patient would benefit from an
evaluation for medically-necessary home care services for skilled assistance with Medication administration
and ADL's (dressing, bathing, hygiene)
Theraples needed:
Physical therapy (to address range of motion, strengthening, mobility limitations), Occupational
therapy (to address fine motor skills, emotional regulation, self-care skills), and Speech therapy (to
address communication and oral-motor skills)

GLOSSARY OF TERMS
We have described some of the terms used here to help you understand them, but you should make sure
to read your benefit plan materials if you have questions.
Anount Billec: The amount your provider billed for the service(s) rendered.
Amount Covered (Allowed): Discounts, reductions, and amount covered (allowed) reflect the terms of
your plan, and in the case of an in-network provider, the savings we have negotiated with your provider.
Your deductible, coinsurance and copay are based on the allowed amount and the terms of your plan.
Your share of coinsurance is a percentage of the allowed amount after the deductible is met.
Coir surance: The percentage of the allowed amount you pay as your share of the bill. If your plan pays
80% after coinsurance of the allowed amount, then 20% would be your coinsurance.
Copay Amount (Also known as Copayment): The set fee you pay each time you receive a certain
service. Some plans do not have copayments.
Deductible: The amount, if any, you must pay before we start paying contract benefits. You do not send
this amount to us. We subtract this amount from covered expenses on claims you and health care
professionals send us. Some services can be covered before the deductible is met.
Non-Participating Provider: An out-of-network provider who does not accept rates for services we set to
keep your costs down.
Out-of-Pocket Limit: Once you pay this amount in deductibles, copayments and coinsurance for covered
services, we pay 100% of the allowed amount for covered services for the rest of the benefit period.
Participating Provider: An in-network or out-of-network provider who accepts agreed-upon rates for
services.

Well-Child Checkup: 6 to 10 Years
Even if your child is healthy, keep bringing them in for yearly checkups. These visits make sure that your
child's health is protected with schedulcd vaccines and health screenings. Your child's healthcare provider
will also check their growth and development. This sheet describes some of what you can expect.
School, social, and emotional issues
Struggles in school can indicate problems
with a child's health or development. If your
child is having trouble in school, talk to the
child's healthcare provider.
Here are some topics you, your child, and the healthcare provider may want to discuss during this visit:
Reading. Does your child like to read? Is the child reading at the right level for thcir age group?
Friendships. Does your child have friends at school? How do they get along? Do you like your
child's friends? Do you have any concerns about your child's friendships or problems that may be
happening with other children, such as bullying?
Activities. What does your child like to do for fun? Are they involved in after-school activities, such
as sports, scouting, or music classes?
Family intcraction. How are things at home? Does your child have good relationships with others in
the family? Do they talk to you about problems? How is the child's behavior at home?
Behavior and participation at school. How does your child act at school? Does the child follow the

Yared. Nehemiah (MRN 11152266) D08: 01/15/2019
classroom routine and take part in group activities? What do teachers say about the child's behavior?
Is homework finished on time? Do you or other family members help with homework?
Houschold chores. Does your child help around the house with chores, such as taking out the trash or
setting the table?
Puberty. Your child will become more aware of their body as they approach puberty. Body image and
eating disorders sometimes start at this age.
Emotional health. Experts advise screening children ages 8 to 18 for anxiety. Talk with your child's
healthcare provider if you have any concerns about how they are coping.
Nutrition and exercise tips
Teaching your child heaithy eating and lifestyle habits can lead to a lifetime of good health. To help, set a
good example with your words and actions. Remember, good habits formed now will stay with your child
forever. Here are some tips:
Help your child get at least 60 minutes of active play per day. Moving around helps keep your child
healthy. Go to the park, ride bikes, or play active games like tag or ball.
Limit screen time to 1 hour each day. This includes time spent watching TV, playing video games,
using the computer, and texting. If your child has a TV, computer, or video game console in the
bedroom, replace it with a music player. For many kids, dancing and singing are fun ways to get
moving.
Limit sugary drinks. Soda, juice, and sports drinks lead to unhealthy weight gain and tooth decay.
Water and low-fat or nonfat milk are best to drink. In moderation (6 ounces for a child 6 years old.
and 8 ounces for a child 7 to 10 years old daily), 100% fruit juice is OK. Save soda and other sugary
drinks for special occasions.
Serve nutritious foods. Kecp a variety of healthy foods on hand for snacks, including fresh fruits and
vegetables, lean meats, and whole grains. Foods like french fries, candy, and snack foods should only
be served rarely.
Serve child-sized portions. Children don't need as much food as adults. Serve your child portions
that make sense for their age and size. Let your child stop eating when they are full. If your child is
still hungry after a meal, offer more vegetables or fruit.
Ask the healthcare provider about your child's weight. Your child should gain about 4 to 5 pounds
each year. If your child is gaining more than that, talk to the healthcare provider about healthy eating
habits and exercise guidelines.
Bring your child to the dentist at least twice a year for teeth cleaning and a checkup.
Sleeping tips
Now that your child is in school, a good night's sleep is even more important. At this age, your child needs
about 10 hours of sleep each night. Here are some tips:
Set a bedtime and make sure your child follows it each night.
TV, computer, and video games can agitate a child and make it hard to calm down for the night. Turn
them off at least an hour before bed. Instead, read a chapter of a book together.
•Remind your child to brush and floss their teeth before bed. Directly supervise your child's dental
self-care to make sure that both the back teeth and the front teeth are cleaned.
Safety tips
Recommendations to keep your child safe include the following:
When riding a bike, your child should wear a helmet with the strap fastened. While roller-skating,
roller-blading, or using a scooter or skateboard, it's safest to wear wrist guards, elbow pads, knee
pads, and a helmet.
In the car, continue to use a booster seat until your child is taller than 4 feet 9 inches. At this height,
kids are able to sit with the seat belt fitting correctly over the collarbone and hips. Ask the healthcare
provider if you have questions about when your child will be ready to stop using a booster seat. All
children younger than 13 should sit in the back seat.
Teach your child not to talk to strangers or go anywhere with a stranger.
Teach your child to swim. Many communities offer low-cost swimming lessons. Do not let your

child play in or around a pool unattended, even if they know how to swim.

Bedwetting: It's not your child's fault
Bedwetting, or urinating when sleeping, can be frustrating for both you and your child. But it's usually not
a sign of a major problem. Your child's body may simply need more time to mature. If a child suddenly
starts wetting the bed, the cause is often a lifestyle change (such as starting school) or a stressful event
(such as the birth of a sibling). But whatever the cause, it's not in your child's direct control. If your child
wets the bed:
Keep in mind that your child is not wetting on purpose. Never punish or tease a child for wetting the
bed. Punishment or shaming may make the problem worse, not better.
To help your child, be positive and supportive. Praise your child for not wetting and even for trying
hard to stay dry.
Two hours before bedtime don't serve your child anything to drink.
:
Remind your child to use the toilet before bed. You could also wake them to use the bathroom before
you go to bed yourself.
Have a routine for changing sheets and pajamas when the child wets. Try to make this routine as
calm and orderly as possible. This will help keep both you and your child from getting too upset or
frustrated to go back to sleep.
Put up a calendar or chart and give your child a star or sticker for nights that they don't wet the bed.
Encourage your child to get out of bed and try to use the toilet if they wake during the night. Put
night-lights in the bedroom, hallway, and bathroom to help your child feel safer walking to the
bathroom.
If you have concerns about bedwetting, discuss them with the healthcare provider.

consumption decreases risk of cancer, diabetes and heart disease. Ensure that your child eats fruits and
vegetables at every meal and as a snack.
2 hours of screen time or less per day: Children who watch more than two hours of screen time (TV,
computer, video games) per day have double the incidence of obesity when compared to children who
watch less than one hour per day. Limit screen time to two hours or less per day and keep children
physically active. Children should not be allowed to watch TV before 2 years of age, and there should bc
no TV in a child's bedroom, no maiter what the child's age.
1 hour or more of physical activity per day: Physical and mental health significantly improves when
children and teenagers obtain their required 60 minutes of physical activity per day. Encourage your child
to be active! Have a goal of 60 minutes a day of moderate physical activity.

INTERPRETATION OF PHQ-9 SCORE
SCORE OF 0 - 4
MINIMAL OR NONE: Monitor, may not require treatment.
SCORE OF 5 - 9
MILD: Use clinical judgment (symptom duration, functional impairment) to determine necessity of treatment.
Support, educate to call if worse, return in one month
SCORE OF 10 - 14
MODERATE: Scoring suggests moderate depression severity; paticnts should have a treatment plan ranging
from counseling, follow-up, and/or pharmacotherapy.
SCORE OF 15 - 19
MODERATELY SEVERE: Patients typically should have immediate initiation of pharmacotherapy and/or
psychotherapy.
SCORE OF GREATER THAN 20
SEVERE: Patients typically should have immediate initiation of pharmacotherapy and expedited referral to
mental health specialist.

In Developmental Pediatrics we believe in a strengths-based view of all children and youth. In our
evaluations we seek to join with the neurodiverse community in moving toward neurodiversity-affirming
language and worldview. This refers to the idea that people have differences in their abilities and how
they interact with the world around them - differences that are not considered deficits. At the same time,
we recognize that the practical use of our reports is often to gain access to services. For these reasons you
will find us using a mix of perspectives. We value the differences neurodiversity brings, while
acknowledging its impact on daily life. We use the terms "disorder" and "disability" to acknowledge this
and to make clear to those who allocate services that the person we are writing about should be
considered eligible to receive these services.

The Childhood Autism Rating Scale (CARS-2) is a behavior rating scale intended to help identify Autism
Spectrum Disorder. The CARs-2 is designed as a rating scale for the trained clinician to rate items
indicative of Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD) after direct observation of the child. The CARS-2 is used
on children ages 2 and older. Areas measured on the CARS-2 include relating to people, imitation,
emotional responses, body use, object use, adaptation to change, visual response, listening response,
tase, smell and touch response, fearlor nervousness, verbal communication, nonverbal communication ,
activity level and general impressioni.
The CARS-2 consists of 15 domains assessing behaviors associated with Autism Spectrum Disorder and
yielding a total score. Each domain is scored on a scale of 1-4, including half scores; higher scores are
associated with a higher level of impairment. Total scores can range from a low of 15 to a high of 60;
and higher indicate severe symptoms. The CARS-2 was completed during today's visit after direct

Medical Assessment:
Eliava is an adorable 3 year 2month old gir with a history  speech delays and an educational
diagnosis of Autism Spectrum Disorder is appropriate for her and to provide guidance on future
supports. Parental history and clinical observation were notable for inconsistent use of non-verbal
methods of communication including pointing and eye contact, inconsistent joint attention, difficulties
with integrating verbal and non verbal modes of communication, and stereotyped language and motor
movements. While she does demonistrate these skills at times, they are inconsistent and not always well
integrated. While there was some engagement with provider during today's evaluation, joint attention
was brief and unsustained, she did hot use integrated eye contact or other non-verbal modalities to
request or engage in joint attention with provider (briefly noted at times with her mother), and play
was parallel in nature. She was observed to flap her hands and use a loud, high pitched vocalization
when excited. She does have notable strengths in areas of imitation and pretend play, as well as an
overall easy going demeanor without significant behavioral challenges. Using information taken from
history, clinical observation, and conduction of CARS-2 rating scale, Eliava meets diagnostic criteria for
a diagnosis of autism spectrum disorder. Recommended levels of support include Level 2 in the area of
social-communication and Level 1 in the area of restricted interests/repetitive behaviors. Additional
diagnoses include her historical diagnosis of speech delays. Eliava has shown great improvements thus
far with the support of her loving family and support of her school team, and is expected to make
further improvements with continued support.

In Developmental Pediatrics we believe in a strengths-based view of all children and youth. In our
evaluations we seek to join with the neurodiverse community in moving toward neurodiversity-affirming
language and worldview. This refers to the idea that people have differences in their abilities and how
they interact with the world around them - differences that are not considered deficits. At the same time,
we recognize that the practical use of our reports is often to gain access to services. For these reasons you
will find us using a mix of perspectives. We value the differences neurodiversity brings, while
acknowledging its impact on daily life. We use the terms "disorder" and "disability" to acknowledge this
and to make clear to those who allocate services that the person we are writing about should be

Medical Assessment:
Bryan is a 6 year old boy with a history of Autism Spectrum Disorder and developmental delays, seen
today in Developmental Pediatrics to establish medical care. Bryan currently attends ABA full time, with
plans to pursue a mixture of ABA and school next year. He also receives speech and occupational
therapies twice weekly. Bryan has difficulties with attention and distractibility that are beyond what we
would expect for developmental level, and are consistent with a diagnosis of ADHD. Vanderbilt forms
provided today for parents and ABA therapists to fill out. Given the significance of his impulsivity and
safety concerns, initiation of stimulant medication was reviewed. He is a picky eater for which updated
lab work will be obtained, although growth is reassuring at this time. He wakes often in the middle of
then night and previously had very low ferritin levels at 5. It is unclear if he has ever taken iron
supplementation in the past, levels to be rechecked. Constipation is currently being managed with
Miralax. He needs updated audiology testing given language delays, however will implement after
ADHD symptoms better treated as they have had significant difficulties testing him in the past. He has
had previous imaging including brain MRI and EEG in November 2023 in the context of developmental
regression and vomiting at the time. EEG with diffuse slowing, brain MRI with non-specific findings at
the time with consideration to repeat in 6-12 months. We reviewed today the potential to repeat
imaging as well as updated lab work while sedated. For significant behavioral challenges, his father is
interested in participating in the RUBl program. Given his Autism Spectrum Disorder diagnosis and
developmental delays, a genetic etiology should be considered.

5. Medication Considerations
a. Due to concerns about Attention/Hyperactivity/Impulsivity we recommend a trial of the
following medication classes
i. Stimulants:
1. Stimulant medications include medications like Methylphenidate/Ritalin and
Mixed Amphetamine Salts/Adderall. They come in both short and long-
acting versions. Many school aged children prefer the long-acting version so
they do not have to take medication at school. Which medication you start
with is often chosen based on desired starting dose, family history of
medication, and what form of medication your child can take (liquid,
sprinkles, pills).
2. What these medications will help with: Stimulant medications are considered
first line treatment for ADHD and can help improve focus, attention,
hyperactivity and impulsivity.
3. All the medications in this group have the same side effects, but whether a
child has a certain side effect can vary between medications in the group.
a. Common side effects:
i. The most common side effects are headache and
stomachache which should resolve within a couple of days
after starting the medication, decreased appetite, and sleep
changes.
ii. Some children will become irritable or emotional; this can
happen throughout the day, or when the medication is
decreasing in their system.
iii. These medications can also increase the heart rate and blood
pressure slightly, but do not cause long term heart problems
in a normal heart
b. Monitoring: While on these medications it is important to have your
child's weight and blood pressure periodically checked.

Plan: Counseling - Plantar Fasciitis.
The vast majority of patients wil improve with a guided program of conservative management. It may take a protracted period of time for symptoms
to diminish
This is the most common cause of heel pain. Plantar fascitis occurs when the fascia (a band of tissue) on the bottom of your foot becomes irritated
and inflamed from overuse. Often there is no identifiable cause. however. it is generally accepted that obesity and repetitive impact sports are risk
factors. Overuse. trauma. and generalized inflammatory conditions may be causative factors as well. Conservative options are fairly broad and
include rest. ice. corrective shoewear. splints. heel pads. or orthotics. foot and toe exercises. massage therapy. and physical therapy. Cortisone

Medrol Dose Pack : I discussed with the patient that this medication is a steroid medication used to treat inflammation. The medication is taken over
a defined penod of days in decreasing doses There are few mild side effects. Nausea, heartbum. and headache are among the more commonly
reported side effects Steroid medication can weaken your immune system and therefore it is important to avoid being in contact with people who
are ill. Blood sugar levels can be increased by this medicine; if you are diabetic, it is important to monitor your glucose closely on this medicine.
Narcotics : I discussed with the patient that these drugs can cause stomach upset, constipation. or nausea. Short term use of these medicines is
recommended because long term use can cause addiction.
NSAIDS : I discussed with the patient that NSAIDs should be taken with food. Prolonged use of NSAIDs can result in the development of stomach
ulcers or bleeding Patient advised to stop taking NSAlDs if abdominal pain occurs. The patient verbalized understanding of the proper use and
possible adverse effects of NSAlDs All of the patient's questions and concerns were addressed
Physical Therapy : Physical therapy focuses on stretching of your calf muscles and plantar fascia There may also be focus on foot and toe
exercises, icing. and therapeutic massage Ultrasound may help to reduce the inflammation Therapeutic exercises can be performed to help the
condition As the symptoms resolve. rehabilitation generally progresses nto more functional activity exercises. such as walking.
Surgical Options and Alternatives
Extracorporeal Shock Wave Therapy : This is a noninvasive procedure that employs high energy shock waves to heal the plantar fascia. The
results with this method of treatment are unpredictable.
Gastrocnemius Recession : During this procedure one of the muscles (gastrocnemius) of your calf is lengthened either through an open incision or
via the use of an endoscope Risks include infection. wound complications, and injury to tendons. nerves. and blood vessels.
Potential for Future Surgery : I explained that though I am not recommending a surgical intervention at this time. this may be recommended or
necessary in the future to alleviate or treat this condition. especially if conservative measures fail or the condition continues to progress or worsen.
Steroid injection : I discussed with the patient that this involves the injection of a potent antinflammatory substance (cortisone) mixed with an
anesthetic into the plantar fascia Risks include whitening of the skin at the injection site and a transient rise in blood glucose. Complications are
rare; infection is the most common. Too many injections may cause rupture of the plantar fascia.

deformity
Steroid Injection : Steroid injections are recommended as pant of plantar fascitis management oftentimes to reduce the swelling of bursitis
associated with the deformity.
Extracorporeal Shock Wave Therapy : This is a noninvasive procedure that employs high energy shock waves to heal the plantar fascia The
results with this method of treatment are unpredictable

The vast majority of patients will improve with a guided program of conservative management. It may take a protracted period of time for symptoms
to diminish
This is the most common cause of heel pain. Plantar fascitis occurs when the fascia (a band of tissue) on the bottom of your foot becomes irritated
and inflamed from overuse. Often there is no identifiable cause. however. it is generally accepted that obesity and repetitive impact sports are risk
factors. Overuse. trauma. and generalized inflammatory conditions may be causative factors as well. Conservative options are fairly broad and
include rest, ice. corrective shoewear. splints. heel pads. or orthotics. foot and toe exercises. massage therapy. and physical therapy. Cortisone
injection may be helptul on a limited basis. Surgical treatment is reserved for those cases that do not respond to conservative management.

Extracorporeal Shock Wave Therapy : This is a noninvasive procedure that employs high energy shock waves to heal the plantar fascia. The
results with this method of treatment are unpredictable.
Gastrocnemius Recession : During this procedure one of the muscles (gastrocnemius) of your cal is lengthened either through an open incision or
via the use of an endoscope Risks incude infection. wound complications, and injury to tendons. nerves. and blood vessels.
Potential for Future Surgery : I explained that though I am not recommending a surgical intervention at this time. this may be recommended or
necessary in the future to alleviate or treat this condition. especially if conservative measures fail or the condition continues to progress or worsen.
Steroid injection : I discussed with the patient that this involves the injection of a potent antinflammatory substance (cortisone) mixed with an
anesthetic into the plantar fascia Risks include whitening of the skin at the injection site and a transient rise in blood glucose. Complications are
rare; infection is the most common. Too many injections may cause rupture of the plantar fascia.
Conservative Options and Alternatives
Functional Orthotics : Functional orthotics are to be used to evenly distribute pressure across the affected area and improve foot biomechanics.
Strapping/Splinting : Strapping and/or splinting align the arch. stretch soft tissues and improve comfort without intending to permanently correct the
deformity
Steroid Injection : Steroid injections are recommended as pan of plantar fascitis management oftentimes to reduce the swelling of bursitis
associated with the deformity.

Plan: Counseling - Equinus Contracture.
Musculoskeletal Care: Treatment depends on the cause of the tendon contracture. Conservative management includes orthotic use, serial casting.
and physical therapy aimed at stretching and strengthening. Shoewear modification may also be advised. Surgery may be indicated if there has
been failure of conservative therapy or a fixed contracture.
Expectations: Contracture of the Achilles tendon can occur for a vaniety of reasons Some people are born with a tight achilles tendon while others
may develop the contracture as a result of prior fracture surgery. a neurologic condition. or compartment syndrome. Chronic wear of high heeled
shoes may put an individual at risk of developing this condtion. Patients typically have limited range of motion of the foot and may have difficulty
putting the heel down on the ground fully. An aching sensation on the back of the ankle may be present The diagnosis is made by clinical
examination of the affected foot.
Contact Office if the pain worsens or you experience increasing ankle weakness.
Active Therapy : Active therapies incude stretching and strengthening exercises for the ankle and adjacent joints.
Passive Therapy : Passive therapies include ice, heat. massage. ultrasound. and electrical stimulation.
